video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text:
AI's answer:        Thought

Short answer: keto is not a cure-all for mental illness, and there’s no credible evidence it “cures 43%.”
But it’s a legitimate area of research—with early, promising (still small) studies—especially as an adjunct to standard care.

What we actually know

Strong, established use: epilepsy (especially drug-resistant, often in children). Multiple reviews show meaningful seizure reduction; this is where keto has the most medical backing. 


Serious mental illness (emerging data): small pilots suggest ketogenic diets may improve symptoms and metabolic health in people with bipolar disorder or schizophrenia when added to usual treatment—but these are feasibility or open-label studies (no or limited controls), not large RCTs. Results = “improvement,” not cure. 


Depression/anxiety: early case reports and planned RCTs exist; evidence is preliminary. 


Why might keto help (the hypotheses)

Ketosis can shift brain fuel use (ketones), affect neurotransmitters (GABA/glutamate), reduce neuroinflammation, and improve insulin resistance—mechanisms relevant to some psychiatric disorders. Evidence here is mechanistic and early-stage. 
PMC

Safety & who should be cautious

Keto can be safe for many with proper supervision, but it’s not benign:

Kidney stones: pooled incidence ≈ 5.9% on keto, much higher than background. 


Lipids & CKD: LDL-C/ApoB can rise; CKD patients are higher risk (acidosis, stones). 
Oxford Academic

Other issues: constipation, micronutrient gaps, “keto flu,” and rare euglycemic ketoacidosis (esp. with SGLT2 inhibitors). 
Frontiers

Bottom line

Keto is evidence-based for epilepsy.

For mental health, it’s experimental but promising as an adjunct, not a replacement for meds/therapy. The “43% cure” claim isn’t supported by current science. Large, well-controlled trials are still needed. 

If you’re considering trying it (with your clinician)

Treat it like a medical trial: continue your psychiatric care; add keto as adjunct.

Prefer a whole-food, unsaturated-fat–leaning ketogenic pattern (non-starchy veggies, olive oil, fish, nuts; limit ultra-processed meats).

Baseline & follow-up labs: lipids, kidney function, electrolytes; discuss meds (e.g., SGLT2 inhibitors, lithium, antipsychotics). 
Oxford Academic

Track outcomes weekly (mood scales, sleep, energy, weight, side effects).

If risks are a concern, consider lower-carb / low-glycemic approaches that have some seizure and metabolic data and are often easier to sustain.

comment_text:
Very interesting video, thanks for posting. 

I have seen the following changes in my health/wellbeing since commencing the Keto diet two weeks ago. 

My skin cleared up within 3-4 days. No pimples, pock marks or spots were observed. My sleeping became more restful as a result of less tossing and turning. My RLS (restless leg syndrome) has disappeared completely. 😳🙏I also had a had a much calmer demeanour throughout the day.  

The biggest and most important change however was associated with a physician diagnosis of ‘pseudo gout/arrhritis)’ that I was suffering from in the top middle of my right foot. It was so bad after going for walks (b/w 5-15ks) that the next day I would be hobbling around and the next night’s sleep was almost impossible as there was no comfortable position that I could place my foot in, that would allow me to sleep. The pain was constantly annoying. (BTW, it wasn’t alcohol-related because I barely drink. 

Amazingly, after only 2 weeks on the keto diet, I can now walk anywhere up to 15ks without ANY pain or inflammation in the foot. I simply couldn’t believe it! 

I’m now continuing on my keto journey for a few months to see what else I can get out of it. I really can’t see myself returning to eat carbohydrates any time in the future because the diet just seems to get me. I’m now down 6kg two weeks after starting the diet. 

Thanks again for posting the interview. I 15:50 hope my story is able to assist others with similar issues. Best regards 🙏

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text:
Ketogenic diet has enormous effect on my psyche. I have always been a "dreamer" and a bohemian. I have in many occasions been very depressed and that has always coincided with the feeling of "going crazy". Incredibly vivid dreams, out of body experiences and a weird feeling of being "watched" all the time. Luckily I have always recovered and today (in my 40's) I have a stable life and business with my life partner. I tried the ketogenic diet for the first time when I was about 30 yoa. It was biblical! All physical issues went away, aking knees, back problems, joint problems and of course, my head became like a well oiled machine. It was like stepping out of the fog. Suddenly I could concentrate like I always felt "everybody else" could concentrate. No more "dips" where I almost fell asleep at work - I now feel wide awake the whole work day and evening, until i just get tired aprox at bedtime, like a clock and I wake up feeling refreshed. I sleep like a king on the ketogenic diet. Teeth - it feels like your teeth is always just brushed, my swollen, red and inflamed gums became flat, bright pink and now look healthy like in a toothpaste commercial. My stomach, WOW.. - it just stopped existing. I forget that I have a stomach - on the ketogenic diet its never swollen, never akes, never talks, no nothing, it just works and does what is supposed to do. Yes of course, it is hard totally switch to the ketogenic diet and quit with all those refined carbs and sugars - you have been an addict since you quit breast feeding, and if you only got the poison of "formula" u are definitely an addict since birth. But I recommend doing the hard why, just quit and change to the ketogenic diet immediatly. Your body will thank you, and if you are over 40 yoa in matter of days your body will feel 20 years younger. If you are a "healthy person", you know the ones "who can eat anything" and still be skinny and have perfect skin, the ones who naturally takes two or three tablespoons out of the ice cream bucket and "feel full" or just stops without thinking about it - these people where made for the high carb diet - and we are different - we where made for the ketogenic diet. Its just as simple as that.
Of course there can be issues in the beginning, like "brain-fog" for a week, feeling heavy and fatigued during workout, and bad breath, but that will goaway, and it is well worth the wait.
Another benefit that people like me - gaining weight incredibly easy and a true sugar addict and ALWAYS hungry or having craves is that I can go for a whole day without eating, YES IT IS TRUE! I still cannot believe it myself. I naturally after about 6 months fell into a routine of eating once a day, at around 4-5pm when I came home from work in the afternoon. Of course, weight quickly became a none issue. I became as skinny as I was when I was 17. But please do not think that the ketogenic diet cures sugar addiction, it does not, it just is an enormous help when you feel the great difference in your body and mind without the blood sugar rollercoaster - it helps ALOT to know that you can feel like a healthy strong human being. You are what you eat. And of course, when I speak of the ketogenic diet, it means ALOT of fat - I had to totally let go of the "fat-scare". I started eating butter, focused on the fat pieces on the meat, several eggs per day - and my body and mind thanked me for it almost immediatly. I remember the third day, I ate breakfast, eggs, bacon, and 17% fat russian yoghurt and my stomach was totally quiet, not a whisper. I felt such calm.. And even though I became very full, I did not feel "bloated" at all - I have now realised that the bloated feeling is 100% connected to grains, sugars, and carbohydrates.

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text:
Love your show. There are a lot of problematic sound bites and conflations in this episode. I see this having eaten keto from 2017-2023. Strict for a few years. For example, she pulls the evolutionary biology card about our ancestors not eating six times per day. Ignoring the fact that they would eat every single bite of carbohydrates (ie) whenever it became available. Another: carnivore and keto are largely elimination diets. A lot of the benefit comes from removing junk/additives. Not necessarily from depriving the brain and body of glucose (which is so important that it has an emergency generation process AKA gluconeogenesis). People also remove foods they are intolerant too. When you complete a metabolic ward study or supervise patient nutrition in person, of course they will get healthier on any reasonable diet. What she didn’t say: yes, strict ketosis can indeed reduce blood sugar in the short term. Over the long-term, fasting blood sugar often rises (as it did for me) due to chronic elevations of stress hormones like glucagon and even cortisol. Very common. Anyone that wears a CGM will still see a roller coaster of spikes and troughs during long-term keto. You simply force your body to waste energy elevating stress hormones and breaking down either dietary protein or even lean tissue to generate glucose. Leptin resistance on keto is also a thing. Fiber, a form of carb, is widely considered the most satiating macro. There’s also a misconception that your body needs high insulin levels to store fat as body fat. Actually, the easiest macro to store as fat is… as the name implies, dietary fat.

Although I don’t advocate it by any means, you can look at the popular  “sugar diet” and see countless stories of people losing significant weight eating higher carbohydrates. The insulin model is incomplete at best.

As she referenced, this diet is best suited for people working on mental health. It’s far from me one-size-fits-all. Even then, cyclical keto is still generally more beneficial and prevents down regulation of key bodily systems induced by the high stress state (ie “like fasting”) of keto.

comment_text: Thank you, Dr. Ede, I am reading your book and happened across this podcast.  I really enjoyed seeing you here and hearing you speak.  Your arguments and explanations are clear and concise and eventually unfold over the entire podcast (fellow listeners, please listen all the way through).  In addition to your obvious expertise and knowledge, you seem extremely thoughtful and deeply caring about people who struggle. And how SEEN I feel by hearing you describe the intense suffering that can result from ADHD, along with your facial and vocal expressions, all of which which directly communicate the profound nature of the disorder as well as your empathic nature.  It is not something that can be printed in a book.  It was also so reassuring to hear acknowledgement of the unique skills honed by the necessary adaptations made in order to feel safe in the world, e.g., hyper-vigilance, that can become one’s sensing superpower, and the lack of a linear life. Very perceptive. I would love to stop my meds, and while I’ve adjusted to eating whole foods and cutting out processed foods, vegetable oils, etc, I have not broken the sugar and refined carb habits.  Now, I’m beginning to embark on a more keto way of life & figuring out what this looks like while not including red meat (for personal reasons), and exploring sweeteners that do not spike glucose. comment_text:
Fiber is scientifically considered necessary for maintaining human health, though technically it's not classified as an "essential nutrient" like vitamins or amino acids because the body doesn't absorb it. However, its health benefits are well-established in the scientific literature, and it plays a crucial role in:

1. Digestive Health

Promotes regular bowel movements and prevents constipation.

Feeds beneficial gut bacteria, which produce short-chain fatty acids (SCFAs) that support colon health and may reduce inflammation.

2. Metabolic Health

Helps regulate blood sugar levels by slowing glucose absorption.

Aids in lowering cholesterol by binding bile acids in the gut.

3. Weight Regulation

Increases satiety (feeling of fullness), helping with appetite control and weight loss.

4. Chronic Disease Prevention

Associated with a lower risk of heart disease, type 2 diabetes, colorectal cancer, and even all-cause mortality in many large-scale studies.

5. Detoxification

Binds to certain toxins and excess hormones (like estrogen) to help excrete them through the stool.

Scientific Consensus

Numerous health organizations — including the World Health Organization, Harvard School of Public Health, and National Institutes of Health — recommend 25–38 grams of fiber daily for adults, depending on age and gender.

If you're wondering whether humans can survive without fiber: yes, technically — but the risk of chronic diseases, poor gut function, and systemic inflammation increases significantly. So while not "essential" by strict biochemical definition, fiber is functionally indispensable for optimal long-term health.

So high fish and high meat diet? Things that give the most vitamin D. There's no mention of vitamin D here. D is a vitamin that most people are deficient in, that vastly strengthens the immune system and when one is deficient can cause terrible depression.

The keto diet may work for some special people, but you dont always have to drastically alter your diet if you are already eating healthily.

People should start by cutting out all processed food, eat a varied organic diet and get a full blood work done to see if vit D and other levels are at recommended levels.

Ketosis is an emergency function we've evolved to survive the absence of the bodies favoured energy source: carbohydrates. It's not a magical life hack. There's so many videos about keto and carnivore etc. And so few that just give the sound basic advice of avoiding the crap that is passed as food today.

All these depressions and diagnoses started recently, so I doubt that it's eating meat and vegetables that is the problem, we've been doing it for thousands of years.

comment_text:
I turned 67 today, and for the past 15 years, I’ve been completely convinced that we truly are what we eat. I’ve spent many years studying nutrition and the connection between food and disease, and I’ve come to a strong conclusion: real health comes from eating organic, whole foods. That’s where you’ll find the real nutritional value. Food supplements of serious companies do help, but it's mainly whole organic food that keeps people healthy.

Exercise is another key part of staying healthy—just 30 minutes a day is more than enough. And for those living in large cities, my honest advice is: get out as soon as you can. The stress and pollution in urban environments can seriously disrupt your insulin and metabolism, which even the best eating habits can't fully protect against.

I really admire Dr. Georgia Ede, the guest I was listening to. She began to question her own lifestyle and eating habits when her work as a psychiatrist didn’t produce the results she expected. She found herself feeling drained by 5 p.m. every day, even though she was only 40 at the time. In contrast, I remember being 40 and staying up for 48 hours straight and still feeling energized—though I know now that kind of habit isn’t healthy either.

My wife, who’s a pharmacist with experience in the pharmaceutical industry, is still shocked at how little most doctors know about nutrition—even at age 62. They’re trained to treat symptoms, not root causes. But it’s not really their fault. Medical schools often don’t include proper nutrition education because the system is geared toward selling medications, supported by funding from big pharmaceutical companies.

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text:
This episode is a masterclass in high-definition placebo effect, cloaked in modern wellness buzz. When people are desperate for a breakthrough—and saturated in transformation testimonials and podcast hype—their nervous system is primed for change. They’re not just starting a new diet; they’re enrolling in a belief system. And belief can be powerful—sometimes even more powerful than the actual biochemistry.

To be fair, keto does have solid science behind it for certain conditions like epilepsy and insulin resistance. But the leap to “keto cures depression, anxiety, and ADHD” is often overhyped—especially when it’s served up with cinematic music and the reverence of a TED Talk meets salvation message. Even intelligent people can get swept into that placebo-powered current.

And here’s the kicker: most people trying keto also overhaul their lifestyle. They sleep more. Cut sugar. Quit alcohol. Go for walks. Track their meals. So if they feel better—was it really the ketones? Or was it the frappuccino detox and basic self-care?

Bottom line: feeling better doesn’t always mean you’ve nailed the cause. When wellness trends become quasi-religious movements (looking at you, biohackers), it’s easy to mistake emotional enthusiasm for clinical evidence.

Watch, take notes—but stay grounded. Don’t confuse the vibe shift for proof.

comment_text:
Only adding my comment in case keto hasn’t worked for some people. I was on keto for over a year and it was not a great diet for me. I know it works well for some, but keto was the closest I ever came to having an eating disorder.  It’s way too strict. Add in the intermittent fasting that is often presented as part of keto, and it really screwed up my body and my relationship with food. Also, the lack of carbs resulted in less success in running/strength training (for me). My body was too stressed. I also didn’t lose that much weight. I found later on that a more balanced lower carb,l diet, with around 100g of carbs a day works best for me. All of my meals have a little carbs, fat, and protein. And I never skip a meal. That’s what works for me and I’ve lost most of my fat taking this approach. 

I will say that I have many friends that have found success with keto! But staying on it 100% of the time seems to be incredibly hard and limiting socially, so not sure how sustainable it is. If they veer away from keto they bloat like crazy. I know I bloat much less now eating carbs with most meals than I did when I was on keto, not 100% sure why. 🤷‍♀️ just my experience in case there are others who have not had success on keto. It’s not for everyone. 

To each their own!

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text:
In speaking about fiber, I think that an important point was overlooked. True, fiber does what Dr. Ede says, and it also is indigestible - *by us. But* it is not indigestible by the microbes in the microbiome of the gut. And that is the key thing fiber is for. That biome is made up of many varieties of microbes, all with DNA that has no particular relation to us. We have some trillions of cells in our body that have our DNA, but there are just as many of these microbes operating symbiotically in us. They perform different functions, usually enabling our own cells to perform chemical transfers between cells, or healing and cell-building functions. In the gut, one of their key activities is to protect and nurture the membrane that separates the bowel from the rest of the body, maintaining the protective barrier that permits only helpful chemicals and microbes to pass through. In this way, it is the first stop for repelling hazardous or poisonous materials from passing into the body as a whole. With fiber, we feed the biome, not ourselves, and like all living things, they also need to eat to stay healthy. This is the principal reason why I will never move to a carnivore diet, but will remain on ketogenic with intermittent fasting. One meal a day seems to work fine for me, giving my body ample room for keto healing during the day. But I am a type-II diabetic and am still working on reversing my insulin resistance. Perhaps one day, I will recover some of my lost flexibility, but for now, I can live with any way of eating that does not return me to that unlivable state of being I once lived.

Oh, one more thing. Forget about losing weight. That's not the point at all. And if you eat properly, your extra will just drop off naturally over time (and not that much time). It's not necessary to beat any speed records with that anyway. It is necessary to regain your health as directly as possible.

comment_text:
The amount of disinformation on her part is staggrering! No question the Keto diet can help people in many ways. BUT, there are zero longterm studies that show it's healthy. What we do know is a huge body of rigorous studies that show eating meat (all cooked meat) is not only unhealthy, it is the leading cause of the number one killer in the US--heart attacks. If that's not enough, high-heat cooking of meat  (grilling, frying, broiling) produces HCAs, PAHs, and AGEs—compounds linked to cancer, inflammation, and oxidative stress. Meat can also contain dioxins, toxic pollutants in animal fat that disrupt hormones and raise cancer risk.

Food for thought.

So while keto can help, it also can cause diseases if a person is on it long-term. Almost any diet can help a person lose weight, but the goal is not to fit into a skinnier casket. The goal ought to be losing weight it in a healthy way. We're all on a journey, and I sincerely hope the very best for everyone.

comment_text: This really is the best talk I’ve ever heard on the subject! Just reading through the comments….a couple things caught my eye. Someone asked about people in other countries not eating keto and not having health issues. First, there are people there who have issues….. it is a lot less and different kinds! Just like the China study book, previous generations made it easier to conclude some case studies because the food of their culture was more consistent and people didn’t move away as much. Second, I heard someone speak of a study that showed that metabolic damage is passed down from mother to child and through generations you could wind up with whole people groups who can tolerate different foods better than other people groups. Also, I’ve Guinea pigged myself for years trying to get healthier because of gout. Well, in 2007 I practiced what’s called the Daniel fast for 3 months with some friends. I couldn’t believe how it affected me! I lost 52 pounds in 3 months, gout symptoms disappeared, slept better and brain fog went away! After 3 months of it I started feeling a bit sluggish so, emotionally I slipped back into eating the standard American diet. Over the years I would resort to that style of eating and it would help a lot in the beginning (3-4) weeks and then I would get some weird stuff going on with me I didn’t understand. Over time, that weird feeling got worse and worse. A while back I learned I had diabetes and knew automatically that my diet was needing some tweaking! I was already eating clean and decided to go ketogenic. I’ve maintained good blood pressure and my blood sugar levels got much better! After connecting some dots I learned that my gout and blood pressure problems weren’t the result of eating meat but rather mixing the fatty foods and sugary foods together! I’m finally feeling level all day long, not just my energy but also my mind and the way I feel emotionally! I don’t have the explosive energy I used to have but I’ll trade that any day for the well being that I feel now! Hope that helps someone.

comment_text:
I definitely do not subscribe to the theory that the keto diet is the ideal diet for humans across the board, let alone those with health issues. There are so many things I could bring up to argue my case. 

First of all, our physiology is not ideally adapted to consume, nor digest the flesh of cows, pigs etc. Biological beings adapted to eating flesh have short intestines. They consume flesh in its pure state (raw - bl00d  and all) , the same state in which herbivores are ideally adapted to consume food from the plant kingdom. The tooth structure of carnivores is also very different from that of herbivores, including humans. 

I do, however, think that there have been adaptations over time for SOME humans due to living in much colder regions where there was little to no vegetation. 

I think for those of us who  originate from tropical climates though, our bodies are best adapted to eating a plant-based diet -  ideally  raw.  I have been on many different diets over the years and made different lifestyle changes. The ONE diet that my body absolutely thrived on most was a raw, plant-based diet. While I was on it, I was doing 80% - 90% raw, plant based. Everything. .  .and I do mean EVERYTHING in my body became balanced and optimized. I stopped getting menstrual cramps, I stopped getting breakouts and my skin was like glass for the first time in my life since I was about 5. I even started to get muscle definition in my arms without doing any strength training, which I had never in my life had before.  I felt light and vibrant and beautiful.   My depressive episodes only lasted a few days at best before my mood would lift again. Anyone who knows me, knows that I  could sometimes be in the throes of depression for months and months at a time. Unfortunately, I went completely off course with this dietary change when my life got uprooted  and I had to move back to the USA.

When I was on the keto diet, however, I didn't feel good at all, even though the excess  weight came off. My skin was a mess! It was oily, yet dry at the same time and my pores became more enlarged.  My skin didn't look plumped up, youthful and firm like when I was on the raw plant-based diet. The way I was looking and feeling was enough for me to realize that the keto diet is NOT the optimal diet for my body at all.

Has anyone else had a similar experience?

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text:
Not going to spend a second with my ethos / credibility, which is the first 15 minutes of this video, getting straight to facts: 

In Georgia's favor, most of what she says is sensible (e.g., subtraction based diet, individualized, dangers of inflammatory foods, refined carbs, processed foods, sedentary lifestyle, stress), but I've got _beefs_ w/ a number of her comments in the first 30' alone: 

*9:12* - Became suspicious of a sales plug with her comment of experiencing results within _"days to weeks"_ if they have the _"Right information"_, which she clearly possesses and is going to spend the next hour telling us about. 

*12:30* - _"I was walking around with sub-optimal mental health", "faltering after lunch", "being completely spent [at end of day]", "being depressed in winter time"… "All of these things we think of as really normal."_ Because they ARE NORMAL. We live in a hyper-techno-industrialized, nature-deprived, corporate materialistic world that has us sat in front of screens 80% of the day, earning barely enough to afford shelter or health insurance. Winter is depressing b/c we're inside w/o sunlight. That's the main driver of the developed world's (UK & USA namely) mental health crisis, not whether you're eating too much fiber… 

*14:00* - following up to 9:12, she plugs her book and then claims a dietary panacea: "I have a variety of strategies", which "resolved all of my physical issues and mental health issues". Has anyone caught a scent of serpentine grease here?

*16:39* - _"it's not coming from saturated fat … or cholesterol"_. There's about a zillion studies over the past 50 years linking saturated fat and LDL cholesterol to chronic cardiovascular disease. Go right now to the NIH website and type in "saturated fat" or "Cholesterol" and have a nice swim in about one million pages of international research on their nutritional affects upon cardiovascular health, BMI, COPD etc. 

*20:40* - _"Anti-oxidant strategy doesn't work"_… really? That's what anti-oxidants do: capture free radicals. Of course if you have so much inflammation / oxidative stress, they'd probably be neutralized, but that's unfair to say it _"doesn't work"_.

*28:08* - what's causing _"chemical imbalances in brain"_ (i.e., of monoamines, GABA, glutamate)? Answer: _"Inflammation and oxidative stress", and then "all kinds of things go wrong depending on who you are ... you might develop Alzheimer's, ADHD, depression, cardiovascular disease"_, and they are all due to a _"metabolic malfunction"_ according to Georgia Ede. If that were the case, then why have cardiovascular diseases and cancer EXPLODED in the late 20th century, but were mysteriously absent before then? Most of the world was eating grains, rice, pulses back in those days. Why was the rate of obesity and heart disease so low? Why do the blue zone inhabitants of Okinawa and Southern Europe, who eat loads of starchy carbs and fibers daily, live to 100+ years, in good mental and physical health? Why in the China Study do villages unequivocally correlate cardiovascular disease w/ cancer? Sure, inflammation causes big problems, but so does all the plaque (i.e., fat & cholesterol) in your arteries, which tends to get lodged in your brain... It's called an aneurysm.

*Somewhere* - she said something about fiber being useless. There were at least 18 Meta-analyses showing statistical significance for fiber intake and decreases in all-cause mortality. You cannot compete with this level of data and international research. 

I've only got enough patience for 30 minutes of review…_

comment_text:
Back in the 70s, my younger brother had severe ADHD to the extent that even on maximum doses of medication he could not function in any organized setting. The doctors and specialists were at their wits' ends and were recommending institutionalization. We saw a Dr. Feingold on a popular talk show called "Donahue" who recommended cutting out all artificial coloring and flavoring from the diet, and it made all the difference. He still needed medication, but the difference was shocking. He was able to go to school and do normal activities. 

It occurs to me that perhaps the artificial colors/flavors were a factor, but by cutting them (esp. in the 70s & 80s), you eliminate most highly processed foods and are left with what likely was a much more ketogenic diet. He ate no candy, but did have things like dried dates as a treat, for example. More meat, fish, whole vegetables, but he also had carbs like potatoes and pasta. Or maybe it was a combination, and the artificial colors/flavors had an impact as well.

I really hate the way DOAC tries to destroy his guest after she left the interview by incrusting some very inaccurate comments contradicting her. Especially when the comments are more opinions than scientific truths proven by multiple RCTs. And of course the method is very unfair.

So DOAC wrote "Dietary fiber is essential for digestive health and overall well being". As fibers are indigestible, I want to know which studies proved that adding indigestible fibers to our food could help digestion, and how they could do that. To me it's a bit like saying that running with an extra load could help to run faster.

DOAC wrote also "It slows down the digestion and absorption of macronutrients through various mechanisms" If it slows down digestion how could it help the digestion? It seems quite contradictory to what was previously stated. And yes, fibers slow down the absorption of carbohydrates: it is certainly a good thing when you eat too much of them but, as Georgia Ede noted it, a better way to avoid glucose and insulin spikes after a meal would be simply to reduce carbs intake. It's a bit like what we say about alcohol, drink your beer/wine with food rather than on an empty stomach. But preferably and for health purposes, it is better to simply avoid alcohol.

DOAC concluded "It also helps improve digestive issues like constipation, diarrhea and irritable bowel syndrome". Just the fact that fiber could treat both diarrhea and constipation is already suspicious. I'd rather say show me the data. Paul Mason for example, showed a RCT on constipation where the participants on a 0-fiber diet had far better outcomes than those eating fibers. It is a bit more logical as I don’t see why adding more bulk to the food could improve transit except, maybe, if your bowel has some intolerance with a particular and irritant fiber so that it wants to dump it as fast as possible. In that case it could help a bit with constipation but at the price of damage to the gut lining.

Personally, having tested for years both a plant-based diet with a lot of fiber and an animal-based diet very low in fiber I can say that I'm now far better on a ketogenic/carnivore diet with almost no fiber. I guess that legumes, nuts and FODMAPs weren't great for me. From what I watched and read I'm certainly not an outlier as many people who transitioned to a carnivore diet have seen their gut health improve. People interested could search Kent Carnivore channel and see what happens when people have gut issues and, very sadly, rely too much on opinion-based advice rather than on science. 

It is a terrifying thing to think that people who have gut issues are encouraged to eat even more fibers while the fibers are, very often, what caused their issues. These people could perfectly lose their colon in the process because they ate these "healthy" fibers supposed to “improve digestive issues like constipation, diarrhea and irritable bowel syndrome”.  

Maybe after all is it the aim? If you have colon issues, eat more fiber, damage your colon, have your colon replaced with a colostomy bag: no more colon issues.
author: @Noegzit

comment_text:
LDL and HDL are not cholesterol.  They are lipoproteins (low density and high density lipoproteins).  The cholesterol found in both are EXACTLY the same molecule and that molecule is extremely crucial for many things in our bodies.  There are however good and bad low density liporoteins (LDLs) and this has mostly to do with how long they hang around in your blood.  The longer they stay in your blood the smaller they get as they keep dropping off cholesterol and triglycerides (and other fat based things like vitamins) to cells where needed and because they circulate in your blood longer they get glycated and oxidized.  It's these small damaged lipoproteins that get picked up by macrophages (the garbage scoopers in our blood) probably because they are deleterious and the liver doesn't want them, and end up in plaque in our arteries.  Regular, healthy, larger LDLs aren't found in plaque as they get picked up by the liver to be recycled rather quickly in comparison to the very small LDLs.  So yes, LDLs matter but mostly because of the situation we create that determines how long they stick around in our blood.  Guess which situations carnivores and whole food omnivores tend to have?

But yes, I agree, it would have been interesting to hear her speak on this.

comment_text:
As a doctor who works in diabetes and endocrinology I agree that a low carb diet spectrum can be very beneficial but don’t become fanatic and obsessive about the way to achieve your levels of ketones ..( there is a way of assessing the degree of ketosis  called Glucose Ketone Index GKI ) and for those interested you can use a calculator on line . 

The reason of my worries is that , a severe ketogenic diet can potentially lead to muscle loss, particularly if not managed properly with adequate protein intake and resistance training, as the body may start breaking down muscle tissue for energy when carbohydrates are severely restricted; this is especially concerning when combined with a significant calorie deficit.

GKI values approaching 1.0 are considered potentially most therapeutic ( in my view the longer you be in this state after achieving your goals the higher the negative impact like muscle mass loss) . 

A GKI of 6–9 indicates a low level of ketosis, which is ideal for weight loss and maintaining health 
MA GKI of 3–6 indicates a moderate level of ketosis, which is ideal for people with type 2 diabetes, insulin resistance, or obesity

Otherwise she would not put out those myths like seed oils causing inflammation, which could not be experiementally verified, study after study. I don't want to doubt all those reports of people feeling better on a keto diet. People like to think in absolutes, glorify their approach and demonize the rest, but I'm starting to think that either what is most helpful for the brain in the short term is very different from what is most helpful for health in the long term, which is what all those nutritional studies focus on, or there is some very significant individual variability, which is not considered in studies, which only show the average. In total, there are annectodes saying animal-based low carb diets dramatically improve mental and physical health (even though the question often remains compared to which diet exactly), while longterm studies point in the opposite direction. My conclusion is, a ketogenic diet seems to act like a reset for the body, especially for people who have developed several intolerances, which allows them to recover and rebalance, but in the long term, a plant-based whole food diet remains the healthier option. It's similar to the situation with fiber - there is positive association between health in general and gut health specifically and yet, for people with significant existing gut issues, avoiding fiber completely seems to be the most effective thing they can do... until the body has re-established balance and can tolerate them again. What's very clear is, a diet high in fast carbs is never a good idea.

comment_text: I'm sorry, but too many ignorants are still talking about calories and counting them as if they have any real value in nutrition. Calories are just heat units, not a measure of nutritional quality! The human body is not a simple engine that burns "fuel" at a fixed rate. It is an adaptive metabolic system, responding not just to the quantity of energy consumed but, more importantly, to the quality and type of nutrients. Especially in a keto lifestyle, calories mean absolutely nothing – what matters is how the body reacts to the source of those calories. 100 calories from sugar trigger a completely different insulin and metabolic response than 100 calories from healthy fats or protein. Still think a "caloric deficit" is the ultimate key? You're ignoring the fact that metabolism adapts, hormones regulate energy use, and macronutrients play a critical role in these processes as well as gut microbiome. So maybe it’s time to stop obsessing over empty numbers and start focusing on the actual biology of the human body.

comment_text:
She's not saying that it is your "fault", and I am sorry it came off that way to you.

Disorders like bipolar and ADHD have a multitude of factors. Genetics are certainly a significant factor, but there are numerous other factors like diet, lifestyle, environment, stress, microbiome status, etc. that all interplay with genetics to result in how much mood and cognition issues manifest in any given individual.

It's not a binary "you either have it or you don't" situation. You certainly can develop issues over time that become diagnosable as a specific disorder. Conversely, even if you've had a disorder from childhood you can decrease those issues over time by addressing the non-genetic factors I mentioned, "curing" or "remitting" the disorder.

comment_text:
Thank you so much for these insights! It felt so frustrating to get all these seemingly contradictive advices everywhere that it feels like a relief to get explanations that tie fragments of knowledge and personal experience together.
For example about the definition of a ketogenic diet: that it doesn't mean that you're  not allowed to eat carbs, but that it is about wheter the diet gets you into ketosis. Which makes the information out there about the ketogenic diet way more compatible with the information out there about an animal based diet, which includes fruits, dairy and honey, and with my personal experience and preferences. I also like the nuance regarding the types of food sources and regarding the health and activity of the individual. And that getting into ketosis is about the right glucose levels, insulin levels and depleting the glucose storage in the liver. So the fact that your glucose levels are in good range doesn't necessarily mean that you are in ketosis and thus in fat burning mode. I also learned that there are gradations of ketosis, that you can switch in and out there, and that that might be more or less comfortable depending on your health status. Also the information about people healing from all kinds of health problems is very inspiring.
This gives me hope and inspiration to keep searching for ways to heal. Also it reassures me that I should trust the signals of my body more. Because many of this I already started to understand intuitively, but it's challenging not to get anxious and too restrictive after absorbing information that seems to contradict personal experience. In this context I also like the distinction between on the one hand aknowledging the biological facts that apply to everyone and on the other hand regarding the personal configuration.

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text:
Warning::: LONG

Honestly, I had gotten so tired of all the Keto talk and anything surrounding this topic. I myself went keto for about a year and noticed several benefits like energy, weightloss, clarity etc.  I have studied wellness my whole life without a degree to show. Just a personal interest. However, this past year my health has taken a toll like I have never experienced before.  I have gained almost 60 pounds in less than 9 months, debilitating joint and muscle pain, strange UTIs I have never had before, constant allergic reactions and dermatitis, severe restless sleep, insomnia, fatigue, GI issues to name a few. On top of this my mental health has absolutely tanked. I have had OCD/Anxiety/Adhd for years but now it seems almost unbearable. I have a literal pharmacy in my closet from all of my prescribed meds.... I have been to urgent care, doctors appointments, and CVS pharmacy more times this past year then in my whole life. To be honest, I know my eating turned worse during a very stressful time but to amass this list of health issues in such a short time is mind blowing. I have tried low carb and stuff but end up giving up as everything seems to be such a battle in modernity. I just said to my partner I am so done with keto talks, there is nothing else to learn..sure it helps some lose some weight and gain energy....yada yada yada but for me it seems pointless. I literally have so many appointments coming up to address various concerns and even I know Pharma isnt the answer. But after years of various supplements, health plans, diet changes, exercise, therapy, etc....one gives up. I am a YOUNG 43 year old woman in Perimenopause and I am almost disabled. I can barely work my part time service industry job and spend the rest of the time recovering from it. I almost didnt listen because I figured its just another Academic regurgitating same stuff and to some degree is true but I think I turned onto this podcast just in time to make a serious change back into Keto full force to see if I can heal. I am slowly losing my life and vision for any future and this podcast has turned this around for me. Thank you Steven for this interview with Dr. Ede and thanks for all to reading. Let us all be filled with health, knowledge and intention to treat our bodies with the utmost respect. Our whole paradigm needs to shift in society. Thanks for reigniting a flame 🔥 I thought burned out.

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text:
@@НаргизаКарабаева-и4з 
I didn't take any medication for my depression. I had thought about it a couple times but I decided against it every single time.

That first year I started Keto? I went dirty keto. I ate mainly McDoubles from McDonald's without the bun or the ketchup, 6 to 8 per meal, 2 meals per day, 12 to 16 total per day, most days. Without the bun and ketchup, you still have 2 thin beef patties, 1 slice of american cheese, a dollop of mustard, diced dehydrated onions, and a couple slices of cheap pickles per McDouble.
Sometimes I'd switch the McDonald's for different restaurant's foods which would consist of more, bigger, beef patties, cheese, eggs, sour cream, bacon, cucumber, avocado, pico de gallo, and guacamole.

That sort of thing for 3 months was enough for the depression to lift.

These days I eat even more strictly, but still dirty by way of mostly from fast food and restaurants. Mostly eat beef patties. I still have bacon, avocado, and onions. I occasionally have cheese or garlic, but both hurt my joints as it turns out and so I try not to indulge too often.
I cut out pico de gallo and guacamole because both are made with lime juice and limes give people margarita burns and that would sabotage my sunbathing.

All-in-all... best health of my life that I've ever been, shockingly.

Edit: Almost forgot. I also now eat sardines (served in water) and cod liver oil.

comment_text:
**Key Takeaways**

### **Introduction: The Power of Nutrition for Mental Health**
The ketogenic diet has gained significant attention in recent years, not only as a tool for weight loss but also as a potential therapy for mental health disorders. Scientific studies and practical experiences reveal impressive results:

- **43% of patients with chronic mental illnesses** such as bipolar disorder, depression, or schizophrenia achieved clinical remission through the ketogenic diet.
- **64% of participants were able to reduce or discontinue their psychiatric medications.**
- Many people report **noticeable reductions in anxiety** within just three days to three weeks of starting the diet.

These findings suggest that the ketogenic diet profoundly impacts the brain and its underlying biochemical processes. But how exactly does it work, and how can it be tailored to individual needs?

---

### **1. Scientific Foundations of the Ketogenic Diet**

#### **a. What Happens in the Brain?**
The ketogenic diet fundamentally changes the brain's energy supply. It reduces inflammation, oxidative stress, and insulin resistance—three primary causes of many mental health disorders. At the same time, it improves the balance of key neurotransmitters such as:

- **Serotonin** (mood),
- **Dopamine** (motivation and reward),
- **GABA** (calming effects), and
- **Glutamate** (learning and memory).

By shifting to fat as the brain’s primary energy source (ketosis), the brain is supplied with ketones, which are burned more efficiently and "cleanly" than glucose. This allows for sustainable healing and regeneration of brain cells.

#### **b. The Role of Ketosis**
Ketosis is a metabolic state in which the body converts fat into ketones, which serve as an alternative energy source. To achieve this state, the following conditions must be met:

1. **Low glucose and insulin levels:** Achieved by drastically reducing carbohydrate intake.
2. **Depletion of glycogen stores in the liver.**
3. **Production of ketones:** These can be measured through blood tests (e.g., beta-hydroxybutyrate levels above 0.5 mmol/L).

In ketosis, healing and maintenance processes in the brain are activated, which are less active in the normal metabolic state.

---

### **2. The Ketogenic Diet as a Therapy for Mental Illness**

#### **a. Study Results**
A study involving 31 patients with treatment-resistant mental illnesses showed remarkable outcomes:

- The patients had been symptomatic for an average of 10 years and were taking five psychiatric medications on average.
- After starting a mild ketogenic diet in a hospital setting, **all patients improved**, and 43% achieved full remission.
- **Metabolic Health:** All patients also showed improvements in their metabolic markers, which is rare in conventional psychiatric care.

#### **b. Challenges and Safety Considerations**
Transitioning to a ketogenic diet can initially be stressful, as it affects brain chemistry and blood sugar levels. Medical supervision is crucial to avoid side effects such as:

- Changes in blood sugar,
- Blood pressure fluctuations, and
- Potential interactions with medications.

---

### **3. Personalizing Nutrition: A Key to Success**

#### **a. Core Principles of Nutrition**
A successful dietary strategy is based on three fundamental principles:

1. **Nourish:** Provide all essential nutrients through whole foods, especially animal-based products.
2. **Protect:** Exclude harmful ingredients like refined carbohydrates and inflammatory vegetable oils.
3. **Energize:** Ensure stable glucose and insulin levels to provide the brain with long-term, clean energy.

#### **b. Personalization Through Trial-and-Error**
Not every diet works the same for everyone. Factors such as age, activity level, existing health conditions, and personal preferences play a role. Adjustments can be made by:

- **Tracking symptoms** to monitor the effects of specific foods.
- **Metabolic testing** to determine individual carbohydrate tolerance.
- **Considering allergies and food intolerances.**

---

### **4. Practical Tips for Starting the Ketogenic Diet**

#### **a. Preparation**
- **Gradual Transition:** Begin by moderately reducing carbohydrate intake to minimize side effects like the "keto flu."
- **Electrolyte Supplementation:** Magnesium, potassium, and sodium can help prevent symptoms like headaches and fatigue.

#### **b. Foods Included in the Ketogenic Diet**
- **Allowed:** Meat, fish, eggs, non-starchy vegetables, healthy fats (e.g., avocado, coconut oil).
- **To Avoid:** Sugar, refined carbohydrates, ultra-processed foods, vegetable oils.

#### **c. Monitoring**
- Use **ketone tests** (blood or urine tests) to ensure you are in ketosis.
- Keep a food journal to track progress and identify potential issues.

---

### **5. Scientific Controversies and Misconceptions**

#### **a. Is the Ketogenic Diet Sustainable?**
The long-term effects of the ketogenic diet are not yet fully understood. However, numerous reports highlight significant health improvements, including:

- **Weight loss,**
- **Stable blood sugar levels,** and
- **Improved mental clarity.**

#### **b. Myths About Fiber**
The belief that fiber is essential for gut health is increasingly being questioned. A ketogenic diet can provide similar benefits to fiber through the production of butyrate (a byproduct of ketosis).

---

### **6. Specific Benefits of the Ketogenic Diet**

#### **a. Anxiety and Depression**
- **Rapid Effects:** Many people report significant reductions in anxiety within weeks.
- **Stress Hormone Regulation:** The diet lowers cortisol levels, which are often elevated in chronic stress and anxiety disorders.

#### **b. Food Addiction and Binge Eating**
- **Hormonal Stability:** The diet stabilizes insulin and appetite hormones, reducing cravings.
- **Better Control Over Temptations:** Many report thinking less about food and feeling full for longer periods.

#### **c. ADHD and Other Neurodivergent Disorders**
- **Link to Metabolic Health:** Studies show that insulin resistance and ADHD often occur together. The ketogenic diet may help alleviate symptoms by improving metabolic health.

---

### **7. Practical Challenges and Psychological Considerations**
Adopting the ketogenic diet involves more than dietary changes. Key challenges include:

- **Behavioral Adjustments:** Addressing emotional and psychological relationships with food is essential for long-term success.
- **Support Systems:** A team approach, including dieticians, prescribers, and therapists, can help individuals navigate the transition and sustain the diet.
- **Keto Flu:** Temporary symptoms like headaches and fatigue can occur during the initial adaptation phase but can be mitigated with proper planning and electrolyte supplementation.

---

### **Conclusion: A Revolutionary Approach to Mental Health**
The ketogenic diet is more than just a dietary trend—it offers a scientifically backed and transformative way to improve both mental and physical health. By reducing inflammation, stabilizing hormones, and providing clean energy sources for the brain, it can:

- Alleviate symptoms of chronic mental illnesses,
- Lower the risk of metabolic diseases, and
- Improve overall quality of life.

**Recommendation:** Anyone interested in trying the ketogenic diet should educate themselves thoroughly, personalize the approach, and ideally seek medical support. With the right strategy, this dietary approach can be a powerful intervention for both the body and mind.

I got myself off ADHD meds too, because my heart rate and BP started to soar. concentrative meditation is helping me survive - no sleepiness through the day and focus is okay. I'll retire in a decade with less money but better health. I am done with mental health meds for life. 
I've started the keto diet from a week (bumped into this video y'day), so let's see how that goes.
You might - or might not - know this, but people like you are a *godsend* for patients like me. God bless you and your colleagues (Dr Sethi and others)

comment_text:
Unless you have very advanced kidney disease, the ketogenic diet has been shown in multiple studies to improve kidney function, even in mild to moderate cases of renal impairment. The below conclusion comes from a 2024 paper on the topic by Dr. Jeff Volek and team:

"There is a considerable body of research suggesting that a very low carbohydrate ketogenic diet is safe in individuals with moderately diminished kidney function, even in studies that had higher protein intake than what is recommended for kidney disease and diets that are not plant-based. The diet can be safely prescribed in patients with T2D (type 2 diabetes) for treating and remitting diabetes even if they have underlying stage 2 or 3 CKD (chronic kidney disease) or reduced kidney function. Beyond safety, mechanistic plausibility, preclinical data, and even some RCT studies suggest that carbohydrate-restricted diets may be beneficial in improving moderate kidney dysfunction and in reducing progression of CKD.

I have struggled with mental health since I was a teenager, I was given all sorts of pills for many years. It totally derailed my life as I was studying at Cambridge Uni. Historically, I'd skip all meals except for one before bed because I'd feel so awful afterwards...

I'm now nearing 30 and thankfully took matters into my own hands a few years back, starting out with cutting out gluten. I effectively gradually went on an elimination diet (the low-fodmap diet) to reduce the inflammation in my gut and treat my SIBO (Small Intestinal Bacterial Overgrowth) as well as addressing the b12d that had resulted. It's a hard one to stick too, but its really helped. 

Turns out that it's effectively a keto-diet, and my intermittent fasting during the day was also putting me into ketosis. This video might be the final piece to my health puzzle, and gives me more determination to stick to my diet which would historically slip and spiral every once in a while.

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text:
@ruejacks those studies don't exist because no one has ever wanted to pay for those studies.  The pharmaceutical companies, which are the major funding source for medical studies are not interested in funding those studies.  The few that are ongoing are fairly small and are being funded mostly by one philanthropic society (the Baszuki Group).  The ketogenic diet is being studied because there is a large signal from people trying it for mental health.  There is no large signal coming from something like the Plant Based diet so no one has any interested in wasting millions of dollars on it.  Considering the Plant Based diet has been around for a long time now and is more popular than the keto diet, if there was a significant signal, it would have been noticed by now.

That said, there is a small signal from just about every diet where people are switching from processed food to healthier whole food.  It's just not as significant as that coming from a whole food ketogenic diet.  I'd also like to remind everyone that a whole food, medical ketogenic diet can be done with an omnivore diet, carnivore diet or plant based diet.

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text: A ketogenic diet has nothing to do with ketoacidosis.  Ketoacidosis occurs when your body cannot produce insulin, therefore cannot get glucose into your cells for fuel.  Since your cells are starving, your body frantically produces ketones in an effort to get fuel into your cells, but our bodies cannot work on ketones alone and in the end we end up with too many ketones and not enough glucose.  On a ketogenic diet, your body is still producing insulin and still getting glucose into your cells and there is no need for your body to produce the amount of ketones that would occur in ketoacidodis.  Like Dr. Ede said in the interview, our body's cells work on a hybrid of fuel.  Our cells for the most part prefer ketones over glucose but if we have high glucose in our blood it uses the glucose first in an effort to get the excess glucose out of the blood as too high glucose, along with high insulin, is detrimental to our health.
author: @reinerschafer1708

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text: Although much rarer, ketoacidosis can also occur when a person is extremely insulin resistant, your beta cells in your pancreas get exhausted and cannot get enough glucose into the cells.  Then once again your body produces ketones to compensate and ends up producing too many ketones as a last ditch effort to stop you from dying from lack of energy in your cells.  If caught in time, this is often how Type 2 diabetics are first diagnosed.

I did come off keto for a while when my living situation changed and i was in a lot of social situations that pressured me into eating carbs and fast food. I felt terrible and I gained all the weight back. 
I now realize I have to treat carbs like a food allergy. My body does not tollerate them.

@@justinebrink4056Sorry I didn’t reply. I stopped keto because I’ve been going through some difficult stuff. It’s a long story. However I want to get back to it. I don’t have much appetite for anything atm. :/ 
If I remained in ketosis, I never really craved anything. What really kicks in after a bit is the emotional connection to food. Like traditions or food from places I loved. It’s always a process. For those who think it’s sad to give up this or that food, on one level you’re right. However it really depends on how food impacts your health and whether or not a person chooses to treat their various conditions through diet. I can  limit my blood sugar and maintain a healthy weight on keto and if I’m doing it right, a bowl of candy or whatever doesn’t tempt me. If I’m doing it right, I’m not white knuckling it. The huge difference with keto, for me, was once I got into ketosis, it takes about 3 days, I’m no longer craving anything. I don’t enter the middle aisles of the grocery stores (where all the processed high fat/sugar stuff mostly is) anymore and if I do, I feel no cravings for that stuff.  
I didn’t eat enough vegetables though. 🤫😂 
I’m getting back to it. Hopefully eggs will remain available and affordable. 😅

comment_text:
@@julielebel1210 it's hard to explain in a few words why your body doesn't require as much vitamin C one a carnivore, but you don't need to supplement wit C. Like with any dietary regimen it can vary greatly in its interpretation. It may surprise you to learn calf liver has more vitamin C than any fruit or vegetable.It's one of the most if not the most nutrient dense foods but many carnivores don't eat (like) liver and won't eat it.
Vitamin K2 is contained in almost all animal products like eggs, milk, cheeses, yogurt, meat, and fish in its most bioavailable form. The only reason I can think of when it might be wise to supplement is if one is supplementing vitamin D3 in ones' diet (carnivore other other) as it's important for optimal absorption of the vitamin D3. As for the rest I would refrain from making general statements as again, a lot depends on whether one eats nose to tail, and incorporates fish, shell fish etc and I would advise anyone considering to change to eating a carnivore diet to take the time and educate themselves as well as make changes gradually. 
How smoothly one can transition successfully depends a lot on what one was eating prior to starting. (there's usually a physical mental/medical indication) For example, there are many long term vegans  who ave destroyed their digestive tract to the point they have no other option than to proceed with a carnivore diet for healing. 
Years of consuming fruit and vegetable containing varying levels of oxalates will have left oxalate (crystals formed from the oxalic acid from seeds(&seed oil) nuts, dark leafy greens, turmeric, pulses, whole grains, sweet potato, etc, that absorbs calcium from the body ) throughout their entire body down to bone and blood levels and caused damage.... very sad because all the while they are convinced they are on the healthiest diet. It will take years for the body to excrete, eliminate the built up oxalate and can be a very painful experience, requiring a lot of patience...
 Ironically the body uses cholesterol to heal and repair the damage, one of its many essential functions.
Sorry, this is getting very long, not my intention so to learn more about oxalate and oxalate dumping I refer you to look up Dr. Sally K. Norton who physically underwent the process of eliminating oxalate from her body and has become world's leading expert. 
I hope this has inspired you to research more and help yourself and loved ones to dispel the false dietary advise we've been led to believe.  
 
P.S Please warn anyone you know who consumes green spinach rich smoothies regularly as 1 cup of spinach contains 3.5 times the "safe" amount of oxalate...    Oh and fibre is contraindicated as a dietary requirement and as an aid to constipation. In fact non soluble fibre is the very worst thing to consume if constipated. Many people argue that carnivore diet is bad because you may not have a bowel movement daily (say meat gets stuck lol) but that's because the nutrient dense food requires much less volume and is mostly absorbed.

comment_text: I have hashimotos (under active thyroid) which both my mum and nan had and then went on to develop diabetes and then dementia, which I was keen not to follow. I’d been also suffering joint pain in my hands and gut issues. I went keto, really just to simplify my diet and help my gut and it’s been a year. I discovered that when I had gluten or diary, the pain in my hands returned but off of both, it’s completely gone. I’m not celiac but clearly my body struggles in some way with gluten and diary (I can have cheese though). I read that dementia is also known as type 3 diabetes (a progression of diabetes). I will stay low carb and gluten free for the rest of my life now. People get all bent out of shape when you say keto, they assume it’s the old atkins diet and I’m eating bacon, cream and butter but I have such a clean, basic diet now and just have cut out all the rubbish - crisps, biscuits, chips, bread, which all have barely any nutritional value. I’ve also lost a bit of weight despite having the same calories per day and am hopeful my thyroid is improving due to the reduced inflammation.

comment_text:
Ketosis cured my numerous mental health illnesses, including many psychotic episodes and paranoid schizophrenia. I was on the verge of killing myself when I saw Christopher Palmer on Andrew Hubermans podcast, and decided that this is the last thing I'm going to try, and if it doesn't work, I would be ready to kill myself. I was already doing "everything right"; clean eating, tons of exercise, etc., but it didn't work. Medications didn't work and only brought massive side effects.

Ketosis worked big time. It took around 2 weeks to see huge improvements, and in a month I was in remission. I've now been in ketosis for over 2 years. First year was keto, 2nd year was keto carnivore, and continuing on this road. As long as I'm in ketosis I don't have any symptoms. 

Ketosis saved my life. From nearly killing myself to thriving; I got into university last year, I'm in the best shape of my life without any effort (I do lift, but I eat as much as I want and don't gain weight), I'm never bloated, no brain fog, always calm and happy. When I do a minor cheat, I start to get paranoid thoughts.

Big thanks to Georgia Ede too. One of the reasons why I stopped fearing red meat.

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text:
YES to everything she's said!  I discovered the keto diet in 2017.  I've lost weight, blurry vision, skin tags, brown underarm spots, stiff joints and muscles, the inability to move well after getting out of the car after riding for a while, cravings for sugar and carbs, total unexplained fatigue, no energy, and probably a thousand other things.  Gone.  I didn't know that seasonal affective disorder, feeling unable to do anything after 5 PM, and the other half dozen other things she mentioned came under the definition of mental illness; I've lost those too!  I'm 67, just adopted a HUGE Labradoodle, work a full-time job at the local community college, which I could never have imagined holding a 40-hour-a-week job before keto, and never felt better in my life.  I missed having a dog when my prior dog died in 2022; I just didn't get any exercise at all after he died.  Boy, am I getting exercise now.  

I remember working in 2019 with a colleague who brought in a huge sugary coffee product every morning to work.  She was a couple of years younger than me, and it was painful to watch her.  She was very heavy.  She forgot simple things.  She made a lot of significant mistakes in her work.  She was always complaining about not getting enough sleep, having to go to bed in the afternoon, or going in to work early in the morning and taking off early to go home and sleep.  Her life was really uncomfortable for her.  She retired a short while after I started work, and I never told her that her diet was wrecking her life.  She ate a LOT of carbs at the meals she brought in to work with her.  I brought in salads with olive and lemon and seeds, and sardines.

When I first went on the keto diet in 2017 it was exactly like an alcoholic going cold turkey, and at that time I didn't know about electrolytes.  I needed electrolytes.  It was a rough three weeks, and for me, maybe six weeks, but I kept going with it and I am SO glad I did.  It's like transitioning a house from burning coal to going solar.  You can't accomplish all of those changes overnight.

I did notice that I got COVID for the first time this past July, and during and after that time I was craving carbs like nobody's business -- plus, it was my birthday, and I deserved a piece of cake and some ice cream, right?  On my birthday?  Only my birthday treats became every-week indulgences.  In the new year now I've started a mostly carnivore diet and I can feel my body responding positively to this, plus all the extra exercise I'm getting, and I feel stronger than ever.  I think there is research saying that COVID messes with your carb cravings.  It's been really hard for me, post-COVID,  to get back off of carbs.

After listening to a Dr. Berg video from a couple of months ago, I started making my own l. reuteri yogurt.  I've got the recipe down now.  It's easy to do.  I buy the best milk and cream I can find.  I'm even giving a little dollop to my dog when I have mine.  That's our dessert.  My dog, by the way, is getting The Farmer's Dog.  I made my previous dog keto dog food every day, which I loved doing for him, and it took a TON of time and effort.  Now I have the choice of The Farmer's Dog, and I'm thrilled.


THRILLED to listen to this podcast.  Thank you for having her on your show.

comment_text: Love this podcast and this episode. However, I wanted to offer some constructive feedback as a fan of this podcast: I am not a fan of the Community Notes. Especially the note on “dietary fiber” which invalidated what Dr. Ede said. I come to this podcast to listen to cutting-edge research and discussions on new topics that are not mainstream and that challenge my current perspective. Adding the community notes like the one on dietary fiber take away from the magic of this podcast by adding disclaimers to what the guests are saying. Cutting-edge research is called cutting-edge because it exposes sharp truths that are hard to hear. The whole purpose of research is to challenge what we know to be true and to confirm new research with additional studies that show repeatability. However, the mainstream narrative is that we already know all there is to know so anything new or outside of the conventional narrative is harmful and wrong. Adding the community note on dietary fiber being necessary (which I have heard from many other keto doctors that it is not) caters to the conventional narrative and bends to the mainstream media like the BBC who criticize the truth-seeking nature of what makes this podcast so important. Further, it reminds me of Steven’s recent episode with Jordan Peterson in which Mr. Peterson says that as soon as Steven is concerned about his reputation, then the magic and quest-driven nature of this podcast will fall away. When I saw this community note, I saw someone trying to cover their ass, not someone trying to search for the truth regardless of all costs. I know it’s not easy, and I have the privilege of being invisible. I appreciate the efforts and sacrifices made in producing this podcast as this podcast has changed my life. Thank you

comment_text: That’s weird reading these stories my wife & I were sold on the Keto diet after talking to friends, we had made our own bread for years, not huge amounts of carbs , we have a well balanced diet , low meat, lots of fruit & veg but we’re convinced maybe we had it all wrong, so we switched to keto and for the first few months really enjoyed it, but we dint notice a slow creeping loss of our health , 6 months in, we both realised everything was such hard work, hard to concentrate, hard to exercise, hard to remember, hard to sleep, we put it down to just life & circumstances. After another weekend were we had both felt very unwell & tired, we met an old friend who happens to be a successful dietitian, , we spoke of our switch to a keto diet, then she listed all the things we felt we were feeling in our bodies, she gave us a list of foods to try and see what difference it makes, to our surprise it was along the lines of what we used to eat , so we switched back to our old way of eating & it felt odd at first but with a few weeks it was like night & day, everything improved, we both agreed we hadn’t felt better in ages. While we loved the keto diet taking low carbs to no carbs is not advisable, certainly not for us, we now eat a healthy all round varied diet with regular fasting but not all the time, so beware of these fad diets just because it worked for this woman in her personal life , I don’t believe it suits everyone. If your like these people in the study she talks of who have serious brain disorders then maybe keto is for you, but for the average person I’d never recommend it. Just eat normally, a well balanced diet of natural unprocessed foods.

I’m not addressing mental illness or psychiatric issues when I make this statement, because there is something there, I’m sure. As far as overall health in a person with no mental health issues, the overwhelming evidence is ketogenic diet is not ideal. There are 5 blue zones in the world where people live the longest, have the lowest levels of heart disease and cancer. Those areas are are Okinawa, Japan; Sardinia, Italy; Nicoya, Costa Rica; Ikaria, Greece; and Loma Linda, California. Very diverse and completely different communities; however, they share one thing in common- mostly plant based and moderate to high consumption of carbohydrates. Which include rice, pasta, potatoes, fruit, and exclude red meat to a large degree. If keto works for you, fine, but I certainly wouldn’t follow her advice.

comment_text:
some interesting takeaways
- ketogenic diet is any diet that lowers insulin levels to the fat burning point. This state is called ketosis. Your body chops fat into ketones which is alternative for glucose for the brain
- ketosis reduces inflammation, oxidative stress and insulin resistance. 
 - how easy and fast you get into ketosis depends on your "metabolic damage" People who more metabolically healthy, young ,athletic may just need to reduce some carbohydrates and get into ketosis. Older, less healthy need to be more strict. Some children get into ketosis after sleep on normal diet because they are metabolically healthy.
 -you can measure ketosis using ketone meter . W hen you reach levels above 0.5 mmol a lot of "metabolic magic "starts to happen because it activates certain pathways in the body and brain - those are recycling, maintenance  and recovery pathways. Thats why Dr Georgia Ede recommends  going into ketosis from time to time for everybody as a way to regenerate body
-ketosis stabilizes appetite hormones so you're not getting those spikes and crashes in glucose which cause spikes and crashes in appetite.
- ketogenic diet is high fat diet with "moderate not excessive" protein and little to no carbs
-ketogenic diet is not  the only way to achieve ketosis, ketosis also happens during fasting - eating nothing or during "fast mimicking" diet - restricting calories to 750 kcal a day. Ketogenic diet is also  "fast mimicking" but it provides normal amount of calories so it can be applied for long time
- you need at least two weeks to start to see the benefits
- ketosis improves metabolic health and mental health
- ketogenic diet is helpful in losing weight

comment_text: Doctor and PhD in Natural Medicine here 👋 From a historical context, it is important to understand and pay respect to those who developed nutrition based approaches for mental health. Nobel prize winner Dr. Linus Pauling and Dr. David Hawkins (author of Power vs Force), published Orthomolecular Psychiatry in the early 70's, which discussed the relationship between nutrition with mental health disorders such as schizophrenia. They're work was groundbreaking, but was heavily criticized and attacked by mainstream medicine and government health agencies. Nonetheless, their work sparked a new field of medicine, "Orthomolecular Psychiatry," which later became broadly known as "Orthomolecular Medicine." In places like Canada, this field has simply become known as "Holistic Nutrition" as the government/College of Physicians wanted to ensure that there would never be any association between the terms/practices of "medicine and nutrition." It is quite the paradox that to this day natural practitioners/researchers are so heavily attacked, while MDs are praised for drawing the same conclusions (decades later) in a field they don't specialize in and have ostracized. I'm grateful that your platform is being used to raise awareness about natural approaches to mental health/disease. It would be amazing to see guests on your show who work specifically in the field of Natural/Holistic Medicine, who can share how far the research has really come. The information Dr. Ede shared is great, but at the same time I think it would be thrilling for your audience to hear the entire picture. Our field has a much richer history than what the interview made it seem and the research and clinical outcomes have advanced in incredible ways worthy of exploration in a future podcast!

comment_text:
Community note at 1:24:28 is false. Many persons stick on purely carnivore diet for several years, without any fiber intake and thrive and don't have any digestive issues... so it is NOT ESSENTIAL for digestive health and overall well-being. 

The second sentence can be true. 

But the last sentence that fiber improves digestive issues is false.

A 2012 study in the World Journal of Gastroenterology found that 100% of patients with chronic idiopathic constipation experienced complete symptom relief (including less abdominal pain, bloating, and straining) after eliminating dietary fiber. Reducing fiber intake also improved symptoms in 50% of participants, while maintaining a high-fiber diet showed no benefits. This suggests that, for certain individuals, fiber—especially insoluble fiber—may worsen digestive issues.

comment_text:
​@@guyhickson7332 I went vegetarian first, but was too much cheese, eggs and milk, so I had to find easy to make recipes, But since then I get a lot of my recipes from the website 'Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine' PCRM, just type either the long name or 'PCRM Recipes'. as there are so many tasty recipes there (I wish someone told me about them earlier). 

They are designed with oversight of their doctors and nutritionalists. They have treat foods too in there, so it's all sorts of meals, mostly easy to make recipes. the key is not to choose all the treat ones lol, but lots of the hearty ones too. 

The benefits are I have no more eczema, no pimples. and lost my belly fat too and became nicely lean all over, I do weights for muscle building because I enjoy it, and am on par with my friends who still eat meat eggs dairy etc but I don't have that unwanted layer of fat most of them do. My endurance improved too.

Also for inspiration and just a good documentary watch 'Game Changers' by James Cameron, Arnold Schwarzenegger and Jackie Chan that follows the rise of plant-based eating in professional sports. Thats now free to watch on Youtube.  

The PRCM recipes will help a lot. You'll notice theres foods you'd think you shouldn't eat, but can because they worked out the fibre content to slow the carb and sugars from absorbing too fast. Thats a key point why these recipes work without causing blood sugar spikes. Best of luck!
