comment_text:
Had severe arthritis in my right hand for many years to the point were my doctor was considering steroid injections. I have also had back pain from a road accident when I was 16. Had followed the government and NHS guidelines on diet for many years, cut out animal fats, used vegetable and seed oils, margarine and limited eggs and dairy. Red meats were very rare in my diet. After my wife passed away 4 years ago I decided to change my diet completely. Eliminated veg and seed oils, started eating lots of eggs, cheese, butter and dairy. Red meat and fish often, particularly pork as it is a major source of essential nutrients. Cook mainly in animal fats. Cut down on carbs but still plenty of fruit and vegetables. Use olive oil and occasionally 'Cold Pressed' rapeseed oil. I cook from fresh or frozen with ready meals a rarity. Mainly a pizza once every couple of months as a treat. Within a year my arthritis had gone, I lost over 2 stone and I have just realised my back pain has gone. Not bad for an old codger aged 77. I can still chase the youngest grandchildren round and play garden badminton with them. My conclusion is 90% of good health is diet!!!! 
Always had backache from the age of 16 when I decided to argue with a van, the van won and I had a broken leg, a back injury and some short term memory brain damage. Over time the brain learns to ignore the pain although it is always present. Suddenly realised my back pain has gone. Says it all really. A real food diet is king!

comment_text:
I've found that it can take time to adjust because your palette is so used to processed foods. It can be helpful to simply reduce carbs/sugars one step at a time. So for example, if you are drinking soda, drop that first and continue your diet as normal. Then once your body becomes accustomed to that, think of what you can eliminate next, like say, bread. Leave berries and other treats like honey as replacements for the high sugar foods you were consuming before. 

Eventually, you won't be reliant on those either. As your sense of taste becomes more refined, you might try some of those old foods again out of nostalgia. This is fine. You'll notice that soda will be absolutely disgusting now. If you didn't crave steak before, you'll find yourself savoring it in a way that you didn't think possible. Above all, be patient with yourself.

comment_text:
@@aronchas No, there is no such thing as "heathly dose of carbs". You of course can eat carbs, some people can achieve ketosis with up to 50g of net carbs/day, but there are not really needed. Many people can do carnivore for years. I'm 45 and did not eat a vegetable since I was 3 (I suffer from heavy fiber intolerance), and no more carbs since 2018. The only thing I get supplementation for is Calcium. 
I don't say you have to do this, or that you shall do this, but we are all individuals and we are all different. 
Ketosis can be tricky, many people eat too much carbs, not enough protein, and struggle with healthy lipids. It's quite a game of finding what works for you, and you need to adjust. I have a 35/65 ratio between protein and lipids, which is not the most common, but it works for me 🙂

comment_text:
I’m so sorry you suffered from a stroke! I am hopeful you are improving day by day. 

There are many more markers to consider with a lipid panel. High cholesterol is not bad for us. Cholesterol is the backbone of all our sex hormones and adrenal health. LDL (low density lipoprotein) can come in two forms; one that is large and difficult to travel to a cell and one that is small. Even though the number is “high” doesn’t mean bad. 

More important markers are HDL (high density lipoprotein) and triglycerides, HDL should be high and triglycerides should be low. Those are true markers of metabolic health. 

We’ve been lied to about cholesterol. The research at no time has made a correlation. It’s about money.

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text:
Yes so true that it IS confusing, which is why I really want to see Dr Stacy Sims and Dr Georgia Ede in an interview together, instead of each doctor pushing their own views without concerting people who have opposite view point (no a criticism, just something I would love to see on DOAC).. 

I think each person different, I am 36yo woman, 47kg for 170cm, no health issues; exercising at least 3 to 5 hours a week, eating well and a lot, and can eat pretty much anything and eat a lot of carbs and whole foods only (no processed foods and sometimes some sweets like french crepes, ice cream but it's rare) and I never gain weight. 

I tried the keto diet just to see if it would change my life like so many other people said (I wanted more energy for the sake of it) and mainly to support my partner who was trying to lose weight and kept failing before trying keto. 

Being on keto was the worst thing I've never felt (dunno if Keto flu or carbs addiction detox or something else ??) but I felt terrible and hungry for something (carbs I guess) all the time! Had terrible night cramping while taking electrolytes supplements, I ate mostly grass fed beef and whole vegetables (like I used to before but removed the rice, bread that was with it and added more fat!). I also almost couldn't walk because I felt too TIRED in my legs all the time!!! 

When I eat carbs, I feel full and not hungry anymore, I never have craving or never snack, also on Keto, I gained a lot of FAT in my legs while I've always been lean! Which matched what Dr Stacy Sims said... 

Then I lost my periods on Keto (it never happened to me) and my cholesterol went up to the roof (I must be a LMHR so I didn't really worry about it) and my blood pressure kept dropping (I usually have very low BP because I used to avoid salt, but forcing myself to eat more guérande salt fixed that and thanks to the keto diet I realized my salt intake was super LOW); and had the WORSE PMS symptoms ever on keto (I never have PMS....)

So I decided to reintroduce carbs (after going Keto, carbs make me even more full than before now XD), my periods came back 2 weeks after carbs reintroduction, and I feel full of energy again, I do even more exercising now! I decided to fast and Keto (or low carb) right after my periods, then add up more carbs after ovulation to support progesterone. And also doing some seed cycling to see what it will do (still trying that rn so I don't have any benefits); I am combining what I've learned from Dr Stacy Sims and Dr Mindy Peltz and my own experience and feelings to see what works for me. (I still want to lower carbs intake for the sake of not developping insuline resistance).

My male partner on the contrary feels extraordinary on the keto diet! He lost about 7kg within 1 month and a half and feels full on the keto diet (while he was eating SO MUCH on high carb diet and always hungry - we had the exact same meals!); so we still eat the same thing but I would add a bit of bread or more fruit at the end of the meal and it works out! 

I was so frustrated to see that I did exactly the same diet as my partner but the results were so different, he felt amazing while I felt like I was dying... and IDK if it's because I wasn't fat adapted (while I'm used to do intermittent fasting for years; each time after my periods so I thought I'd adapt fast to keto) or if it's because of some genetic variation. Because when we used to eat more carbs with my partner, he'd gain so much weight and I wouldn't... We didn't even eat processed foods or a lot of sweets!! (appart from butter, yogurt : those kind of minimally processed foods)

So yea... I really don't know, I think that there's a lot of individual variations that must be taken into account, and also the male/female difference like Dr Stacy Sims said, women should work with their cycle, but I see so many woman on the carnivore diet and keto diet thriving!!! So it must really come down to individual variation I guess... in the end, try everything for at least a cycle or two and see how you feel! N=1 science above all!

 Switching to ketosis can be unpleasant, but not dangerous.
• Metabolic flexibility can be disrupted by poor nutrition.

45:35 Foods and the Keto Diet

 The keto diet lowers insulin levels by activating fat burning.
• It is important to understand what increases and decreases insulin levels.
• Fat has almost no effect on insulin levels, which makes it a safe macronutrient.

46:54 Definition of Ketosis

 Ketosis is determined by the level of beta-hydroxybutyrate in the blood.
 To achieve ketosis, it is necessary to reduce glucose and insulin levels.
• The liver begins to break down fat when carbohydrates are low.

49:51 The Importance of Ketosis

 Ketosis is necessary for the healing and recovery of the body.
• All people need to be in a state of ketosis periodically.
 Ketosis can be achieved in many ways, including calorie restriction and a Mediterranean diet.

51:05 Nutrition and Ketosis

• Proper nutrition can lower your insulin levels overnight.
 A balanced diet can lead to ketosis without the need to reduce carbohydrates.
• Children can achieve ketosis naturally, unlike adults.

53:35 The effect of nutrition on neurodivergent disorders

• Nutrition may play a role in the development of neurodivergent disorders in children.
• It is important to consider that children can achieve ketosis naturally.
• It may take several days for adults to achieve ketosis.

comment_text:
@@samuelgibbons1221 Because you are doing low carb, but if you do a clean keto, with (like me) no more than 5 g carbs a day, you will stay in ketosis (even the minimum marks it's still ketosis). If you are young and in a good health, make a lot of sport, you can go to 50 g a day and stay in ketosis. It really depend on people and the type of keto diet you are making.
You also need to improve your fat intake, take care of the protein (it depend on a lot of factors, like for me at 59 yo I need more proteins than my daughter who is 40) and eat very carefully your vegetables (remind you, 100g lettuce is around 3 g of carbs). You need to avoid absolutely all the keto crap like breads or pastries even if they are very low carbs. 
If you stay in this type of clean keto diet, it will be very easy to stop any craving, to go effortless to one meal a day, and to have all the benefits of this diet, beyond your expectations.
(in my case, after 13 months in it: 25kg less, no more pain in any joints (was a lot before), no craving (ex bulimia), the sleep is way better, straight 7 hours without going to pee one or two times a night like before, mood balanced, all day long the same power, no naps after food, urine leaks finished, and a lot of little other benefits. I'm certain I was sliding to T2 diabetes, now I'm certain I'm safe.)
By the way, kudos to you @lanagrahamntx; hope you a very long and healthy life (in keto😜). Love from France.

@@bmook019 First, if you had a good knowledge of the ketogenic diet you would know that my case is a very common one. More and more of scientists, even out of the ketogenic sphere, are aware of the irrelevance of the calories and I don't give a lot of years before it will be debunked or at least seen as a clue but not a law.

comment_text: @@bmook019An uninformed assumption, at best. After nine months on strict  keto, I actually gained weight, since I was slightly underweight. My triglycerides, at the top of ideal range, went to bottom of ideal range. My VLDL, previously at the top of ideal range, went to the bottom of ideal range, so a 100% decrease in both. My cholesterol stayed the same. Doctors have warned me for years that the vertebrae in my neck would start to fuse because of two automobile injuries. After six years on keto, they have not further degenerated or fused and are still pliable.  I had a knee replacement scheduled in 2018 because the pain was so bad I could hardly walk. After three months on keto I no longer had to use any pain medications to hike 3 to 5 miles a day with my dog. I am still able to do this seven years after that first knee replacement was scheduled and canceled. I had been through enormous trauma, which I will not specify, but it was significant. It was so bad, I was starting to worry about early dementia when I was in my 50s. I just could not think as clearly as I used to and was having memory issues. After six months on keto, I had the brain I had in my 20s. I couldn’t believe it! That was not something I anticipated experiencing.  There are people with many more dramatic stories than mine, but mine had nothing to do with weight loss and everything to do with keto.

comment_text: Varicose veins are driven largely by inflammation so a ketogenic diet could be very helpful because it reduces inflammation. However the foods you choose to eat on a ketogenic diet also matter because even some keto-friendly foods can cause inflammation in some people. In my book Change Your Diet Change Your Mind I go into a lot more detail about which foods are best avoided on a ketogenic diet to quiet inflammation--for example dairy, nuts, and eggs are culprits for some people. So if a standard ketogenic diet doesn't help with varicose veins then some tweaks to food choices are worth exploring.

comment_text: If you are in good ketosis for at least 3 months the cravings will usually get a lot better--one of the troubleshooting tips in my book Change Your Diet Change Your Mind is that if you still have strong cravings you may want to set dairy aside for a short while to see if they go away. If you're doing well on keto and don't have cravings but you just miss having something decadent from time to time, you might be someone who can indulge a few times year and get right back on track, but many of my patients with carbohydrate addiction find that one day of splurging can throw them off track for days, weeks, or even months, so tread lightly...Also there are keto-friendly desserts that will allow you stay in ketosis and if you miss sweet taste the keto-friendly sweetener I recommend most is allulose.

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text: Although I am very grateful for doctors who have the courage to share their knowledge, which is not approved by most doctors, I am also amazed at how certain topics in relation to nutrition and (mental) health are simply left out. For example, there are certain SNP, i.e. single nucleotide polymorphisms, i.e. norm variants that occur quite frequently, such as slow COMT. These people can break down chatecholamines poorly. This includes, among other things, stress hormones, oestrogens, histamine, thyramine and other biogenic amines (these are found in foods, even or mostly in healthy ones). If this COMT enzyme is too little active, this leads to the accumulation of stress hormones, oestrogens and above all neurotransmitters such as dopamine, serotonin, histamine and other activating neurotransmitters and this in turn leads to sometimes severe psychological symptoms, like severe insomnia and anxiety. Especially with a ketogenic diet this can be aggravated because this diet increases the endogenous chatecholamines.

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text:
@ It‘s a genetic test. There are a lot of different SNP related to the COMT activity. 
The most studied single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) in the COMT gene is the Rs4680, also known as Val158Met. This polymorphism causes a substitution from a valine (Val) to a methionine (Met) at amino acid position 158, leading to a three- to four-fold reduced activity of the COMT enzyme.

comment_text:
To those who say to “just cut out ultra processed foods”. Yes, that’s a great start. But what we are talking about here - the ketogenic diet - is a specific metabolic state where your body and brain utilises fat for energy. This has unique benefits and differences from using glucose as energy. Some people find it makes them more energetic and improves their mood. If you want to argue against the ketogenic diet then it should be based on which metabolism you believe to be better or worse than the other. That’s really the crux of this discussion. (Also check out interviews with Chris Palmer who goes more in-depth about the metabolic theory of mental health). They’re starting to study this theory but it’s still early days. 

Stay open minded folks 😀❤

comment_text: @@Tonisuperfly Try reverse searing. It's like a cheaper version of sous vide. Essentially you start by slowing cooking in the oven at a low temp to help enzymes in the meat tenderize it, and then finish with high heat on the stovetop for the tasty browning portion. Yes, cooking at a lower temperature will preserve the nutrients.

comment_text: @ how low does the temperature have to be to preserve nutrients?
author: @Tonisuperfly

video_title: The Keto Psychiatrist: What Keto Is Really Doing To Your Body! Can It Cure 43% Of Mental Illness?
comment_text:
@@Tonisuperfly Find any guide on reverse searing on the internet and they will typically recommend 225-250F for an even cook. 

The thing is it's not simply the temperature that matters, it's the time as well. If you cook a steak at 225, but leave it in the oven for 5 hours, you will have an overcooked steak.

Just keep the principles in mind that lower heat and lower time spent cooking are best for nutrient preservation, and go from there.

There will always be some nutrient loss from cooking, but at the same time, flavor is important too. I wouldn't overthink it.

If you are on carnivore, you will not be nutrient deprived.

comment_text:
@@Mtn_Mama-i6f could be an unpopular opinion but it seems to me that many medical professionals are super well trained except for in things that don’t directly benefit Big Pharma. 

I say this because I haven’t just noticed this with nutrition and my illness but also other areas too. 

For example I was having a terrible side effect to an antipsychotic they put me on. It was really bad and thankfully my mom started to advocate for me because I was in a manic episode

She kept insisting the over the top side effect was due to one of my meds 

She first thought this because the symptoms of the side effect increased when they upped that med 

But my psychiatrist and another medical professional on my care team kept telling her the symptom couldn’t be from that med and instead kept saying it’s just one of my mania symptoms 

My mom ended ip researching so much and it was so hard to find but eventually she found law suits by people against the company for the same symptom 

After she presented that info they finally agreed to take me off and boom my crazy embarrassing side effect was gone 

Made me wonder how many other people are out there doing crazy things and being told it’s due to their illness rather than the med. 

Actually so many of my BPD symptoms are also symptoms some experience from the meds I’m on

I know I definitely have bipolar but I’m just saying sometimes we have to dig deep for appropriate care.

I have other examples like this too. 

Will be documenting my keto journey on my channel in case you’re interested in following along. Thanks again

comment_text:
@thebipolarboss so excited for you!! You're going to need a few things in my  opinion. I'm not a doctor.

You'll need: a list of brainstorm meal ideas,  a list of allowed and disallowed ingredients and extra disallowed (ex. Glutenand sugar at no costs!), brainstorm & research condiment options and other new product solutions like almond crackers or jicima wraps or monk fruit etc because the time when the cravings hit will not be a good time to buy those.. its too late,  a plan for what you'll do to need cravings met or what to eat when you want to eat something special or different (ex. Guacamole and low carb chips, or keto muffins, keto chocolate fudge, bacon butter bites etc, learn how to make broth GAPS meat stock soup broth if possible,  and lastly, you're going to need epsom salt baths and activated charcoal for detoxing. Activated charcoal is a binder, it can only be taken 2 hours away from anything important.  So if Important meds are at 1 and 5 then charcoal can only be at 3pm.  Learn about detoxing to help you feel better. Headache, tiredness,  achiness, worsened mood instability, eyes hurting etc- could all be the need to detox. Keto diet almost always needs to involve detoxing.  Also you might like the book gut and psychology syndrome  by neurologist nutritionist Dr Natasha Campbell Mcbride. 

I'm cheering you on!! 🎉  my best friend from high school as well as my cousin both have a bipolar-schizophrenia situation.   I think they'd both improve drastically on a Gluten free keto diet.

Love this video!!

comment_text: I have been diagnosed with Bi-polar disorder. I have to diet and exercise religiously, and if I do that, I feel pretty stable. No medication necessary. I don't feel so all over the place and mood swingy. I don't feel anxious and depressed and irritable. And so help me God, if I get off work and eat Taco Bell once, I will start feeling like crap all over again the next day. If you eat once a day, that will help a ton even if you don't watch what you eat. Doing keto is probably better if you can't make it through the day without eating. I was on a mood stabilizer called lamotragine for a while. It made my head hurt and feel really irritable at first, but it did help me a lot. It made me feel like doing stuff and lose weight. I started thinking happy thoughts again, but it made me think a little slower and I didn't like that. A lot of people don't talk about the potentially permanent side effects of psychiatric medication. I swear my sleep is still messed up from antidepressants. And I still don't think my brain functions the same from the mood stabilizer. I can't say if that's a good or a bad thing. It's just different.

comment_text: I don't follow a keto diet or anything, but a little over a year ago, I quit soda and junk food. I started out keeping my total calories under 2200 and getting at least 150g protein everyday. I started losing weight immediately. Then I rolled in more exercise. Then I stopped eating the "low fat" versions of things. Fat makes you feel full so you eat less total volume. For carbs, fats, and even protein, quality matters. Carbs from vegetables are better than carbs from sugar. Fat from animal sources are healthier than seed oils. My sleep apnea went away. My lactose intolerance is gone. The difference in my general health is huge. I developed healthy habits to where I don't have to track calories and macros anymore. It seems more expensive to eat healthy because until your metabolism is repaired, you still want the same amount of food to feel full, but it's remarkable how much less you need to eat if you use some basic strategies. At least it was for me.

comment_text: ​@@happyaslarry5839​ unless you're an 'all or nothing' person, it's good to ease into keto slowly. Week 1 remove all refined sugar, week 2 remove all grains (wheat, corn, rice, oats etc), week 3 remove white potatoes and seed oils, week 4 remove all fruit and other starchy veg. A gradual approach will help prevent adaptation symptoms, aka 'keto flu' which is actually just carbohydrate withdrawal, and will also mean you start switching over to a fat burning state in an easier fashion. Oh, and while you're transitioning, start each day with just fat and protein (eg bacon and eggs cooked in butter) as you'll be going into ketosis overnight (if you have a long enough gap between dinner and your first meal), and starting the day like this will ensure you continue in that state for longer. Georgia Ede has different meal plans at the back of her book, which vary in carbohydrate amount. Very helpful.
